<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1411,1589]" box="[151,754,1564,1589]" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">IHAK 67 Under the Pruth Bay dock. Two small specimens.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,1634,1986]" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">
This is a large species, orange or reddish-orange in color, often up to 
<quantity box="[946,1017,1635,1662]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" unit="cm" value="10.0">10 cm</quantity>
in length but 
<quantity box="[1179,1249,1634,1662]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" unit="cm" value="15.0">15 cm</quantity>
specimens have been recorded (
<bibRefCitation author="Ritter, W. E." box="[325,458,1671,1697]" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" pagination="589 - 616" refId="ref17588" refString="Ritter, W. E. (1900) Some ascidians from Puget Sound, collections of 1896. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, 12, 589 - 616. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1749 - 6632.1899. tb 54995. x" type="journal article" year="1900">Ritter 1900</bibRefCitation>
). Although both siphons are at the anterior end, the atrial siphon is somewhat recurved (
<figureCitation box="[160,264,1707,1733]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1266,1291]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1247]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[151,1435,417,1247]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12.A–D: Pyuridae; E, F: Molgulidae.A: Halocynthia aurantium 10 cm in length; B: Halocynthia igaboja; C: Boltenia villosa; D: Pyura haustor; E: Molgula pacifica whole animal left side, tunic removed; F: M. pacifica close-up of siphons. Scale bars: B, 5 mm; C, 5 mm; D, 5 mm; E, 1.6 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3371910/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">Fig. 12A</figureCitation>
). The tunic is thickly covered with small rounded papillae with very short spines projecting from the top of each papilla. There are longer minutely branched spines around the siphons. It is closely related to the North Atlantic 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rathke, 1806)" authorityName="Rathke" authorityYear="1806" baseAuthorityName="Rathke" baseAuthorityYear="1806" box="[250,581,1779,1806]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Pyuridae" genus="Halocynthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurogona" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pyriformis">
<emphasis box="[250,403,1779,1805]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">H. pyriformis</emphasis>
(Rathke, 1806)
</taxonomicName>
but based on an extensive comparison of the two species by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ritter, W. E." box="[1282,1431,1779,1805]" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" pagination="427 - 505" refId="ref17791" refString="Ritter, W. E. (1913) The simple ascidians from the northeastern Pacific in the collection of the United States National Museum. Proceedings of the U. S. National Museum, 45, 427 - 505. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.45 - 1989.42 7" type="journal article" year="1913">Ritter (1913)</bibRefCitation>
, there are distinct differences such as number of gonads, pattern of tunic spines, and length/width ratio. 
<bibRefCitation author="Van Name, W. G." pageId="23" pageNumber="424" pagination="1 - 476" refId="ref18197" refString="Van Name, W. G. (1945) The North and South American ascidians. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 84, 1 - 476." type="journal article" year="1945">Van Name (1945)</bibRefCitation>
summarized these differences. In the NE Pacific this species’ native range extends from Alaska to Washington (
<bibRefCitation author="Huntsman, A. G." box="[239,435,1887,1913]" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" pagination="111 - 148" refId="ref16158" refString="Huntsman, A. G. (1912 a) Ascidians from the coasts of Canada. Transactions of the Royal Canadian Institute, annals 1911, 9, 111 - 148. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 1313 6" type="journal article" year="1912">Huntsman 1912a</bibRefCitation>
, b; 
<bibRefCitation author="Van Name, W. G." box="[477,664,1886,1914]" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" pagination="1 - 476" refId="ref18197" refString="Van Name, W. G. (1945) The North and South American ascidians. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 84, 1 - 476." type="journal article" year="1945">Van Name 1945</bibRefCitation>
; Lambert CC 
<emphasis box="[826,876,1887,1913]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">et al</emphasis>
. 1996). It is also native in the NW Pacific and is extensively cultured for food in northern 
<collectingCountry box="[621,688,1924,1950]" name="Japan" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">Japan</collectingCountry>
, while wild specimens are collected for food in 
<collectingCountry box="[1236,1304,1924,1950]" name="South Korea" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">Korea</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1362,1437,1923,1949]" name="Russia" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">Russia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lambert, G. &amp; Karney, R. C. &amp; Rhee, W. Y. &amp; Carman, M. R." box="[159,386,1959,1986]" pageId="23" pageNumber="424" pagination="59 - 66" refId="ref17154" refString="Lambert, G., Karney, R. C., Rhee, W. Y. &amp; Carman, M. R. (2016) Wild and cultured edible tunicates: a review. Management of Biological Invasions, 7, 59 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.3391 / mbi. 2016.7.1.0 8" type="journal article" year="2016">
Lambert 
<emphasis box="[262,312,1959,1985]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="424">et al</emphasis>
. 2016
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
